            <m>P(1, m_{1})\;</m> and <m>Q(1, m_{2})</m> gives us the following set up. \begin{mfpic}[18]{-5}{5}{-5}{5} \point[3pt]{(0, 0), (1.5, 0.75), (1.5, -3)} \arrow \reverse \arrow \polyline{( -4, -2), (4, 2)} \arrow \reverse \arrow \polyline{( -2, 4), (2, -4)} \polyline{(1.5, 0.75), (1.5, -3)} \tlabel(1.2, 1){<m>P</m>} \tlabel(-.5,-.6){<m>O</m>} \tlabel(1.2,-3.55){<m>Q</m>} \axes \tlabel[cc](5,-0.5){<m>x</m>} \tlabel[cc](0.5,5){<m>y</m>} \end{mfpic} The line
            <m>y = m_{1}x</m> will be perpendicular to the line
            <m>y = m_{2}x</m> if and only if <m>\bigtriangleup OPQ</m> is a right triangle.
